Maps and visualization For guidance on how tointerpret anduse this table, please see Section1.a.
a.
Implementation specifications OGC's Web MapService is the primaryspecificationfor requestingmaps and visualization via the World Wide Web.Its "GetMap" requests are preceded by a "GetCapabilities" request to ascertaina server's available "layers" of information,and its rendering andprocessing abilities.
ISO's draft Web Map Server Interface (ISO 19128) is basedonthe OGC Web Map Service specification.
Step-by-step tutorials for setting up an OGC Web Map Server are available from NASA's ESIP Federation and International Interfaces, Inc.
OGC has based twoadditional interface specifications on its Web MapService: StyledLayer Descriptor defines an XML syntaxfor portrayal rules that tell an OGC Web MapServer how torender either its owndata or the output of anOGC WebFeature Server or WebCoverage Server.
Web MapContext Documents defines an XML syntaxfor creating,storing,and exchangingmap views from the WebMapService.
As for map encodings: because maps are pictures rather than complexdata,they employ commonraster formats such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG), the Joint Photographic Experts'Group JPEG / JFIF and JPEG2000 (a.k.a. ISO/IEC 15444); TaggedImage File Format (TIFF), or vector formats such as W3C's Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), ANSI/ISO's Computer Graphics Metafile (CGM), or W3C's WebCGM (a profile of CGM).
Maps mayalsobe encoded using simple coverage encodings suchas GeoTIFF,listedin2.b.i above.The choice of map encoding depends on the graphical content to be conveyed (e.g., continuous vs.discrete color variations; transparency; color depth) and the capabilities of the client viewer.
b. Abstract models
Page 13 of 28
FGDC GAI Geospatial InteroperabilityReference Model v1.1
http://gai.fgdc.gov/girm/v1.1/
Despite the widespreaduse of maps andvisualization, there has been onlylimited formal definitionof portrayal processes: ISO's Portrayal draft standard (ISO 19117) defines rules for portraying geospatial features.
OGC's initial WebMapService specification summarizes the chief concepts of user interactionwith geospatial data andinteractive portrayal.
5.
Geospatial Reference Systems Geospatial reference systems identifygeospatial locations, usingeither place names or numeric coordinates.
As such, theyunderlie most geospatial data transfers and service invocations.Table 6describes the standards that guide the choice and expressionof geospatial reference systems.
Numeric coordinates EPSG database 
